<BlogPost
  title="What is Liveness Detection? A Developer's Guide"
  description="Passive vs active liveness, how anti-spoofing works, and how to add it to your app in 10 lines of code."
  date="2026-03-14"
  readTime="8 min read"
>

<p><strong>Liveness detection</strong> answers one question: is the face in front of the camera a real, live person — or a spoofing attack?</p>

<p>Without liveness detection, face recognition systems are trivially defeated by holding up a printed photo, playing a video on a phone, or using a 3D mask. Every production biometric system needs anti-spoofing.</p>

<h2>Types of Spoofing Attacks</h2>

<table>
  <thead><tr><th>Attack</th><th>Description</th><th>Difficulty</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td><strong>Print attack</strong></td><td>Printed photo held in front of camera</td><td>Trivial</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Screen replay</strong></td><td>Photo/video displayed on phone or tablet</td><td>Easy</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Video replay</strong></td><td>Pre-recorded video of the victim</td><td>Easy</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>3D mask</strong></td><td>Silicone or 3D-printed face mask</td><td>Hard</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Deepfake</strong></td><td>AI-generated face injected into video stream</td><td>Hard</td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<h2>Passive Liveness</h2>

<p>Passive liveness analyzes a <strong>single image</strong> to determine if it's a real face or a spoof. No user interaction required — the check happens invisibly.</p>

<p>How it works: a neural network (typically MiniFASNet or similar) is trained on millions of real and fake face images. It learns to detect subtle artifacts: moire patterns from screens, paper texture, color distribution anomalies, depth cues.</p>

<pre><code>// Passive liveness is included in every detect call
const result = await ob.faces.detect(photo);
const isLive = result.faces[0]?.liveness?.is_live;  // true or false
const score = result.faces[0]?.liveness?.score;       // 0.0 to 1.0
</code></pre>

<p><strong>Strengths:</strong> Zero friction, works on any photo, fast (~10ms)<br/>
<strong>Weaknesses:</strong> Can't detect high-quality video replays or deepfakes reliably</p>

<h2>Active Liveness</h2>

<p>Active liveness asks the user to perform <strong>specific actions</strong> — blink, smile, turn their head. The system verifies each action was performed correctly using facial landmark tracking.</p>

<p>This is much harder to spoof because the attacker would need to generate real-time responses to random challenges.</p>

<pre><code>// Create a liveness session with specific challenges
const session = await ob.liveness.createSession({'{'}
  challenges: ['blink', 'turn_left', 'smile'],
  ttl_seconds: 120,
{'}'});

// Submit frames as user performs actions
const result = await ob.liveness.submitFrame(
  session.session_id,
  videoFrame
);

// Check if challenge passed
console.log(result.passed);              // true
console.log(result.challenges_remaining); // 2
</code></pre>

<h2>Challenge Types</h2>

<table>
  <thead><tr><th>Challenge</th><th>What user does</th><th>What system checks</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td><code>blink</code></td><td>Blink eyes</td><td>Eye Aspect Ratio drops below threshold</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>smile</code></td><td>Smile naturally</td><td>Mouth width / face width ratio increases</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>turn_left</code></td><td>Turn head left</td><td>Head yaw angle exceeds -15 degrees</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>turn_right</code></td><td>Turn head right</td><td>Head yaw angle exceeds +15 degrees</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>look_up</code></td><td>Look upward</td><td>Head pitch angle exceeds threshold</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>look_down</code></td><td>Look downward</td><td>Head pitch angle exceeds threshold</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>open_mouth</code></td><td>Open mouth wide</td><td>Mouth Aspect Ratio exceeds threshold</td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<h2>Presets for Common Use Cases</h2>

<p>OpenBiometrics includes pre-configured challenge sets for different security levels:</p>

<table>
  <thead><tr><th>Preset</th><th>Challenges</th><th>Security</th><th>Best for</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td><code>passive_only</code></td><td>None (MiniFASNet only)</td><td>Basic</td><td>Low-risk, zero friction</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>eye</code></td><td>2x blink</td><td>Medium</td><td>Phone unlock</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>smile</code></td><td>1x smile</td><td>Medium</td><td>Customer onboarding</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>head_turn</code></td><td>Turn left + right</td><td>High</td><td>Defeats flat photos</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>full</code></td><td>4x random</td><td>Highest</td><td>Financial KYC</td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<h2>Passive + Active Combined</h2>

<p>The strongest approach combines both: passive liveness runs on every frame (catching obvious spoofs immediately), while active challenges prove the person can respond to real-time prompts.</p>

<p>This two-layer approach stops:</p>
<ul>
  <li>Print attacks (passive catches texture)</li>
  <li>Screen replays (passive catches moire patterns)</li>
  <li>Video replays (active challenges are random each time)</li>
  <li>Deepfakes (active liveness with head turns is extremely hard to fake in real-time)</li>
</ul>

